ing many who freely invoke the Tenth Amendment, seemed to be attacking the progressive state for asserting states’ rights. Unusual as this may seem, this has happened before—in the early part of the twentieth century, as America concluded a decades-long struggle over the suppression of alcohol during Prohibition. Sean Beienburg recovers a largely forgotten constitutional debate, revealing how Prohibition became a battlefield on which skirmishes of American political development, including the debate over federalism and states’ rights, were fought. Beienburg focuses on the massive extension of federal authority involved in Prohibition and the passage of the Eighteenth Amendment, describing the roles and reactions of not just Congress, the presidents, and the Supreme Court but political actors throughout the states, who jockeyed with one another to claim fidelity to the Tenth Amendment while reviling nationalism and nullification alike. The most comprehensive treatment of the constitutional debate over Prohibition to date, the book concludes with a discussion of the parallels and differences between Prohibition in the 1920s and debates about the legalization of marijuana today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aFederal governmentzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFederal government-United States-History-20th century. 0aProhibitionxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProhibitionzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aProhibition-Political aspects-United States-History-20th century. 0aProhibition-United States-History-20th century. 0aUnited States.-Constitution.-18th Amendment. 0aUnited States.-Constitution.-21st Amendment. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAl Smith.  aAmerican political thought.  aCalvin Coolidge.  aTenth Amendment.  afederalism.  amarijuana.  anul